{{short description|French coroner and forensic pathologist}}
'''Philippe Charlier''' is a French [[coroner]], [[Forensic pathology|forensic pathologist]] and [[Paleopathology|paleopathologist]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lhistoire.fr/m%C3%A9decin-des-morts-r%C3%A9cits-de-pal%C3%A9opathologie|title=Médecin des morts. Récits de paléopathologie|date=December 2006|website=[[L'Histoire]]|language=fr|accessdate=30 October 2018}}.</ref>

==Biography==
Charlier was born in [[Meaux]] on 25 June 1977. His father is a [[Physician|doctor]], his mother a [[pharmacist]]. He made his first dig at the age of 10, when he found a human skull. He studied [[archaeology]] and [[art history]] at the Michelet Institute and was part of the forensic department at [[Raymond Poincaré University Hospital]].<ref name="Libe2006">{{cite web|url=http://www.liberation.fr/portrait/010168776-comme-un-poisson-dans-l-os|title=Comme un poisson dans l'os |date=9 December 2006|website=Libération|language=fr|accessdate=30 October 2018}}.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/livres/2011/06/28/03005-20110628ARTFIG00397-philippe-charlier-l-homme-qui-revelele-secret-des-morts.php|title=Philippe Charlier, l'homme qui révèle le secret des morts|date=28 June 2011|website=[[Le Figaro]]|language=fr|accessdate=30 October 2018}}.</ref> His work has focused on the study of the remains of [[Richard Lionheart]], [[Agnès Sorel]], [[Fulk III, Count of Anjou]], [[Diane de Poitiers]], relics of [[Louis IX]] scattered in France, false relics of [[Joan of Arc]], and the presumed head of [[Henry IV of England|Henry IV]].<ref name=parisien>{{cite web |url=http://www.leparisien.fr/societe/philippe-charlier-le-medecin-des-tetes-couronnees-09-10-2011-1644951.php|title=Philippe Charlier, le médecin des têtes couronnées|date=9 October 2011|website=[[Le Parisien]]|language=fr|accessdate=30 October 2018}}.</ref><ref name="bmj2010">{{cite journal|journal=BMJ|date=2010|issue=341|page=c6805|doi=10.1136/bmj.c6805|title=Multidisciplinary medical identification of a French king's head (Henri IV)|pmid=21156748|authors=Charlier P, Huynh-Charlier I, Poupon J, Keyser C, Lancelot E, Favier D, Vignal JN, Sorel P, Chaillot PF, Boano R, Grilletto R, Delacourte S, Duriez JM, Loublier Y, Campos P, Willerslev E, Gilbert MT, Eisenberg L, Ludes B, de la Grandmaison GL|url=https://www.bmj.com/content/341/bmj.c6805}}</ref> In 2017, he reconfirmed [[Death of Adolf Hitler#Aftermath|Hitler's dental remains]] from a jawbone fragment in the Soviet archives.<ref>{{cite book|last=Brisard|first=Jean-Christophe|last2=Parshina|first2=Lana|year=2018|title=The Death of Hitler|publisher=Da Capo Press|isbn=978-0306922589|pages=224, 273–274}}</ref>

