{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2014}} {{Infobox writer | name = Sophie Radford de Meissner | image = Sophie_Radford_de_Meissner,_circa_1910-15.jpg | image_size = | alt = Posed portrait from Bain News Service | caption = Circa 1910–15 | birth_name = Sophie Adelaide Radford | birth_date = {{Birth date|1854|11|17}} | birth_place = [[Morristown, New Jersey]], U.S. | death_date = {{Death date and age|1957|4|17|1854|11|17}} | death_place = [[Washington, D.C.]], U.S. | resting_place = [[Oak Hill Cemetery (Washington, D.C.)]] | occupation = {{Flatlist| * Novelist * playwright * historian * [[spiritualism|spiritualist]] }} | language = English | relatives = [[William Radford]] (father) }}
'''Sophie Adelaide Radford de Meissner''' (November 17, 1854 – April 17, 1957) was an author, playwright, diplomat's wife, spiritualist and socialite.<ref name=SARD>{{cite web|title=Grave Site: Sophie Radford de Meissner|url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/58167177|work=Oak Hill Cemetery, Lot 916, Washington, D.C.|publisher=Find A Grave|accessdate=November 1, 2012}}</ref>
==Childhood== Sophie was born third of seven children to [[William Radford]] (September 9, 1809 – January 8, 1890), an officer in the [[United States Navy]], and Mary "Minnie" Elizabeth Lovell (April 12, 1829 – October 27, 1903). All the Radford children were born in [[Morristown, New Jersey]] except Henry, who was born in [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref name=Vermilye>{{cite book|last=Vermilye|first=Anna S.|title=Ogden Family History|year=1906|publisher=The Orange Chronicle Company|location=Orange, New Jersey}}</ref>{{RP|77}}
The Radfords resided with their in-laws, the Lovells, on Mount Kemble Avenue in a house previously owned by General John Doughty.<ref name=Colles>{{cite book|last=Colles|first=Julia Keese|title=Authors and Writers Associated with Morristown|year=1895|publisher=Vogt Brothers|location=Morristown, NJ}}</ref>{{RP|210–212}} At the close of the [[American Civil War]], the Radfords moved to [[Washington, D.C.]] Sophie attended Madam Burr's School near Fourteenth Street and New York Avenue where the language was [[French language|French]] only, regardless of the subject. She took her [[grand tour]] when her father received command of the [[European Squadron]] in early 1869 and took his wife and six children to accompany him to Europe.
As Radford performed his naval duties in the Mediterranean Sea and European west coast, his family sailed with him to Spain, Portugal, [[Algiers]], France, the Netherlands, and Italy. During 1870, Sophie and siblings attended school at [[Lausanne]], [[Switzerland]]. A month after the outbreak of the [[Franco-Prussian War]], her father relinquished his command and went to Lausanne to retrieve his children believing any battles would be distant. After arrival in [[Paris]], the [[Battle of Sedan (1870)|surrender]] of the French Army on Sep 2, 1870, caused the Radford family to flee the [[Siege of Paris (1870–1871)|advancing Prussian Army]]. At [[Le Havre]] they negotiated commercial passage to the United States.<ref name=DeMeissner>{{cite book|last=de Meissner|first=Sophie Radford|title=Old Naval Days|year=1920|publisher=Henry Holt and Company|location=New York}}</ref>{{RP|329–371}}
==Marriage and family== On February 22, 1877, Sophie fell from her horse while riding in [[Rock Creek Park]] and fractured her skull. She remained unconscious into March. Among callers to the family was Waldemar de Meissner, first secretary of the Russian [[Legation]]. They married November 20, 1877 in two ceremonies: first at the [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopal Church]] and then at the Radford residence on 1736 (now 1734) N Street NW in the [[DuPont Circle]] neighborhood. Attendees included [[President of the United States|President]] [[Rutherford B. Hayes]] and [[William Tecumseh Sherman]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Our Regular Correspondent|title=An International Wedding: The Daughter of an American Admiral Wedded to a Russian Nobleman|newspaper=Unknown; from a clipping|date=November 20, 1877}}</ref>
During the next 20 years, de Meissner's diplomatic career took them to [[Saint Petersburg]], [[Bern]] and [[Lisbon]]. Their only child was a son, Alexandre (also known as Sacha), born September 24, 1878. Sacha was educated in a military college in Russia and rose to the rank of [[Cornet (military rank)|cornet]] in the 44th Regiment of [[Dragoon]]s of the [[Imperial Russian Army]].<ref name="Death Notice">{{cite news|title=Mme. de Meissner, 102, Writer, Socialite, Dies|newspaper=Unknown; from a clipping|date=April 16, 1957}}</ref>
In the spring of 1896, Sophie travelled to Russia to visit her son. Waldemar remained in Lisbon, but contracted pneumonia and died during her absence, on April 17, 1896. Sophie moved back to Saint Petersburg to be near her son, accepting a position as [[lady-in-waiting]] to another widow, the [[dowager]] [[List of Russian consorts|Empress of Russia]], [[Maria Feodorovna (Dagmar of Denmark)|Maria Feodorovna]]. Three years later, Sacha contracted a throat infection and died on August 28, 1899. Sophie returned to Washington, D.C., widowed and childless at age 45, to reside at her mother's [[Georgetown (Washington, D.C.)|Georgetown]] home.<ref name=Yates>{{cite book|last=Yates|first=Robert Somerville Radford|title=A History of William Radford of Richmond, Virginia|year=1986|publisher=Amundsen Publishing Company|location=Decorah, Iowa}}</ref>{{RP|6–27}}
==Writing career== Sophie wrote for magazines, many articles based upon her experiences abroad.<ref name=Magazines>{{cite web|last=Unz|first=Ron|title=Author: Sophie Radford de Meissner|url=http://www.unz.org/Author/DeMeissnerSophieRadford|work=UNZ.org|accessdate=December 25, 2013}}</ref> Among them are: * "A Happy Accident" appeared in ''[[Scribner's Magazine]]'', April 1888, pp.&nbsp;461–479. * "Under Police Protection: An Episode in the Life of the Late Chief of the Russian Police" appeared in ''Scribner's Magazine'', December 1892, pp.&nbsp;772–778. * "Two Tests" appeared in ''[[The Forum (defunct magazine)|The Forum]]'', June 1924, pp.&nbsp;803–805. * "The Wild Horseman, Count Chandor" appeared in ''Wide Awake'', November 1888 * "The Origin of "The Magic Flute"" appeared in ''Wide Awake'', September 1889 * "How the Cossacks Play Polo" appeared ''Wide Awake'', August 1891
Many of her books are still in publication and include: * ''The Terrace of Mon Desir'' (1889) * ''The Tscherkeese Prince'' (1892) * ''There Are No Dead'' (1912) * ''Old Naval Days: Sketches from the Life of Rear Admiral William Radford, U. S. N.'' (a biography of her father) (1920) * ''Rachel Ogden'' (1928) * ''The Shepherd King'' (1931)
The Russian play [[The Death of Ivan the Terrible|"Ivan the Terrible"]] was written circa 1866 about [[Ivan IV Vasilyevich]], who ruled as the first [[List of Russian rulers#Tsars of Russia|Tsar of All the Russias]]. The play was one of a trilogy written by Count [[Aleksey Konstantinovich Tolstoy]], a cousin of Count [[Leo Tolstoy]]. She attended a production of the play in Russia and determined to translate it into English. In 1901, Sophie sent the play to theatrical agent [[Elisabeth Marbury]] to show to actor [[Richard Mansfield]].
Mansfield signed a contract with Sophie February 1, 1902 to star in and produce the play. The play premiered March 1, 1904 on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] in the [[New Amsterdam Theatre]] with Mansfield performing the title row. Mansfield kept the role in his repertoire until his death.<ref>{{cite book|last=Wilstach|first=Paul|title=Richard Mansfield: the Man and the Actor|year=1909|publisher=Charles Scribner's Sons|location=New York, New York}}</ref>{{RP|406–409}}<ref>{{cite book|last=Winter|first=William|title=Life and Art of Richard Mansfield|year=1910|publisher=Moffat, Yard and Company|location=New York, New York}}</ref>{{RP|272–274}}
In 1902 during a return trip to Russia, she translated the second play of Tolstoy's trilogy, [[Tsar Fyodor Ioannovich]].<ref name=NoDead>{{cite book|last=deMeissner|first=Sophie|title=There Are No Dead|year=1912|publisher=Sherman, French & Company|location=Boston, Massachusetts}}</ref>{{RP|39}}
==Spiritualism== Sophie became a proponent of [[spiritualism]]. Her book ''There Are No Dead'' is a collection of conversations with deceased family, friends and others. The first entry was recorded twelve hours after the death of her son. She made newspaper headlines in 1912 when she requested an audience with President [[William Howard Taft]] after the sinking of the [[RMS Titanic|Titanic]]. She said she had a message to deliver from a victim of the sinking, [[Archibald Butt]], who was an aide and close friend to Taft.<ref name=NoDead/>{{RP|102–112}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Maj. Butt's return – spiritually, of course|url=http://jacksonville.com/tu-online/stories/061798/nef_allfoley.html|work=The Florida Times-Union|accessdate=December 26, 2013}}</ref>
Two other victims of the Titanic sinking and also associated with Taft, [[William Thomas Stead]] (also a spiritualist) and [[Francis Davis Millet]] are said to have communicated with Sophie.<ref name=Whiting>{{cite book|last=Whiting|first=Lilian|title=The Adventure Beautiful|year=1917|publisher=Little, Brown and Company|location=Boston, Massachusetts|pages=101–13}}</ref>
==Legacy== During a visit to Saint Petersburg in 1905, she served in the [[International Red Cross and Red Crescent Movement|Red Cross]] to tend casualties from the [[Russo-Japanese War]].<ref name=Kennedy>{{cite news|last=Kennedy|first=George|title=Party for Mme. de Meissner Recalls Her 100 Years of Life|newspaper=The Evening Star, Washington D.C.|date=November 18, 1954}}</ref>
Articles in the society pages of Washington D.C. from the early 1900s mention her at gatherings as a speaker for Russian culture, clothing, etc. Her 80th birthday celebration was noticed in the society pages of the Miami Daily Herald.<ref>{{cite news|last=Jarvis|first=Jean|title=Capital Events Now in Honor of Debutantes|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2206&dat=19341125&id=MSJVAAAAIBAJ&sjid=Zj0NAAAAIBAJ&pg=6463,3314980|accessdate=December 26, 2013|newspaper=Miami Daily News|date=November 25, 1934}}</ref>
Sophie spent the last seven years of her life in the Washington D.C. Home For Incurables. At her 100th birthday party, 40 guests, including 3 nieces, attended.<ref name="Death Notice"/><ref name=Kennedy/>
Letters to her niece Edith Lovell (Coyle) Matthes, wife of [[François E. Matthes]], are stored in the François Matthes papers collection, Carton 3, Folder 51, in the [[Bancroft Library]] at [[University of California, Berkeley]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Finding Aid to the François Matthes Papers, 1874–1965, bulk 1900–1950|url=http://www.oac.cdlib.org/findaid/ark:/13030/tf7199n8zj/entire_text/|work=Collection Number: BANC MSS C-B 821|publisher=The Regents of the University of California|accessdate=December 26, 2013}}</ref>
Letters to Julia Keese Colles are stored in the Colles Family Papers, Box 4, Folder 37, in the Morristown and Morris Township Library.<ref>{{cite web|title=Finding Aid to the Colles Family Papers, 1807–1946|url=http://morristownlibrary.org/HCFindingAids/Collesfamilyead.xml|work=North Jersey History and Genealogy Center|publisher=Morristown and Morris Township Library|accessdate=December 26, 2013}}</ref>
